{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":3145787,"name":"mahim","username":"Mahim","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/mahim/{size}/65240_2.png","created_at":"2023-02-15T10:03:32.576Z","cooked":"<p>I really appreciate the fact that we are moving towards functional programming with commands, and having specific classes for instances where you’d want to just pass in method references for actions you want to do instead of writing fully blown classes. As well as different classes that get different types of commands like <code>InstantCommand</code>, <code>RunCommand</code>, <code>StartEndCommand</code>.</p>
<p>But lets say you want a command that runs as long as a button is pressed and do an action when its stopped you either have to make a FunctionalCommand where it can look something like this:</p>
<pre><code class="lang-java">Command runEnd = new FunctionalCommand(
  () -&gt; {},
  runFunc,
  isFinished; 
  () -&gt; endFunc(), 
  subsystem);
</code></pre>
<p>or simply chaining and <code>andThen()</code> after a <code>RunCommand</code>. But what if you need to define an isFinished logic if you want the command to end early? Theres no predefined class where you just pass in method references for execute, isFinished, and end. You could just use the <code>FunctionalCommand</code> and leave the init: <code>() -&gt; {}</code> to do nothing. But personally I believe it can get confusing, or cumbersome to always having to define each part of a Command when you’re not even using it.</p>
<p>I think it would be really helpful if we have a <code>CommandBuilder</code> class where we can pass in the methods you want to reference, and the command builder will build a command with only those parts and not having to pass in a “do nothing” section. It can look something like this:</p>
<pre><code class="lang-java">Command betterCommand =  new CommandBuilder()
  .execute(runFunc)
  .isFinished(false)
  .end(endFunc)
  .build(subsystem);
</code></pre>
<p>I think this design pattern can be beneficial in some instances than using a FunctionalCommand:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>you can define <code>isFinished()</code> with a boolean OR a <code>BooleanSupplier</code> while you still have to pass <code>() -&gt; false</code> if you use <code>FunctionalCommand</code>.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>same with <code>end()</code> you can pass in a <code>Consumer&lt;Boolean&gt;</code> or a <code>Runnable</code> instead of having to ignore the boolean if you just want to pass an action where it doesn’t matter if the command was interrupted or not.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>this way you don’t have to define sections of the command you want to leave empty. You are forced to define every part in a <code>FunctionalCommand</code>. The <code>CommandBuilder</code> object can start off with the init &amp; exec to do nothing, isFinished as returning true, and end to do nothing unless you change it by using the chain methods.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>it is easier to read. having to pass in every part of the command through the constructor can be confusing, and you have to remember which order to put them in. But using a builder pattern you can pass them however you want, and easier to understand which parts you’re adding in without fancy intellisense.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<pre><code class="lang-java">// you wouldn't know which is doing what with an untrained eye...
Command runEnd = new FunctionalCommand(
  () -&gt; {},
  runFunc, 
  () -&gt; false; 
  interrupted -&gt; endFunc(),
  subsystem);

// vs.

Command betterCommand =  new CommandBuilder()
  .execute(runFunc)
  .end(endFunc) // takes a Runnable
  .end(interruptedEnd) // or a Consumer&lt;Boolean&gt;
  .isFinished(false) // takes a boolean
  .isFinished(() -&gt; false) // or BooleanSupplier
  .build(subsystem);
</code></pre>
<p>and the inside can look something like this:</p>
<pre><code class="lang-java">import edu.wpi.first.wpilibj2.command.Command;
import edu.wpi.first.wpilibj2.command.FunctionalCommand;
import edu.wpi.first.wpilibj2.command.Subsystem;

import java.util.function.BooleanSupplier;
import java.util.function.Consumer;

public class CommandBuilder {
  private Runnable init = () -&gt; {};
  private Runnable execute = () -&gt; {};
  private BooleanSupplier isFinished = () -&gt; true;
  private Consumer&lt;Boolean&gt; end = interrupted -&gt; {};
  private Subsystem[] requirements;

  public CommandBuilder() {}

  public CommandBuilder init(Runnable init) {
    this.init = init;
    return this;
  }

  public CommandBuilder execute(Runnable execute) {
    this.execute = execute;
    return this;
  }

  public CommandBuilder isFinished(BooleanSupplier isFinished) {
    this.isFinished = isFinished;
    return this;
  }

  public CommandBuilder isFinished(boolean bool) {
    this.isFinished = () -&gt; bool;
    return this;
  }

  public CommandBuilder end(Consumer&lt;Boolean&gt; end) {
    this.end = end;
    return this;
  }

  public CommandBuilder end(Runnable func) {
    this.end = ignore -&gt; func.run();
    return this;
  }

  public CommandBuilder addRequirements(Subsystem... subsystems) {
    this.requirements = subsystems;
    return this;
  }

  public Command build() {
    return new FunctionalCommand(init, execute, end, isFinished, requirements);
  }

  public Command build(Subsystem... subsystems) {
    return new FunctionalCommand(init, execute, end, isFinished, subsystems);
  }
}
</code></pre>
<p>Do you guys think this would be something useful?</p>","post_number":1,"post_type":1,"posts_count":7,"updated_at":"2023-02-15T11:05:22.176Z","reply_count":2,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":223,"reads":110,"readers_count":109,"score":1162.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":426881,"topic_slug":"using-a-builder-pattern-for-functional-commands","display_username":"mahim","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":2,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":1}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":29279,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/using-a-builder-pattern-for-functional-commands/426881/1","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":1}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":1,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null,"can_vote":false},{"id":3145794,"name":null,"username":"Starlight220","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/starlight220/{size}/150872_2.png","created_at":"2023-02-15T12:15:27.655Z","cooked":"<p>I recommend looking at the new command factories (some in the <code>Commands</code> utility class). Command composition is somewhat similar to what you’re suggesting, and is far more powerful and flexible.</p>
<p>With the building blocks of <code>runOnce()</code> (aka InstantCommand) and <code>run()</code> (aka RunCommand), combined with decorators such as <code>until()</code>, <code>finallyDo()</code>, <code>andThen</code>, etc., you can really do anything via command compositions.</p>
<p>Some recommended reads:</p>
<ul>
<li>Included building-block commands (this includes FunctionalCommand, among others): <a href="https://docs.wpilib.org/en/latest/docs/software/commandbased/commands.html#included-command-types" class="inline-onebox" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">Commands — FIRST Robotics Competition documentation</a>
</li>
<li>API docs of factories in <code>Commands</code>: <a href="https://github.wpilib.org/allwpilib/docs/release/java/edu/wpi/first/wpilibj2/command/Commands.html" class="inline-onebox" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">Commands (WPILib API 2023.3.2)</a>
</li>
<li>Command compositions: <a href="https://docs.wpilib.org/en/stable/docs/software/commandbased/command-compositions.html" class="inline-onebox" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">Command Compositions — FIRST Robotics Competition documentation</a>
</li>
</ul>","post_number":2,"post_type":1,"posts_count":7,"updated_at":"2023-02-15T12:15:27.655Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":1,"reads":84,"readers_count":83,"score":41.8,"yours":false,"topic_id":426881,"topic_slug":"using-a-builder-pattern-for-functional-commands","display_username":null,"primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://github.wpilib.org/allwpilib/docs/release/java/edu/wpi/first/wpilibj2/command/Commands.html","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"Commands (WPILib API 2023.3.2)","clicks":7},{"url":"https://docs.wpilib.org/en/latest/docs/software/commandbased/commands.html#included-command-types","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"Commands — FIRST Robotics Competition documentation","clicks":6},{"url":"https://docs.wpilib.org/en/stable/docs/software/commandbased/command-compositions.html","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"Command Compositions — FIRST Robotics Competition documentation","clicks":3}],"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":2}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":45763,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"6738a | ISR | WPILib"},"post_url":"/t/using-a-builder-pattern-for-functional-commands/426881/2","custom_user_title":"6738a | ISR | WPILib","reactions":[{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":1},{"id":"point_up","type":"emoji","count":1}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":2,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},